Introducing preterm birth and the dataset

Today, we will be using a publicly available dataset looking at the vaginal microbiota in preterm birth. The results of the authorâs research has been published in a peer reviewed journal. If you are interested, you can read the original article by Callahan et al., here.

What is preterm birth?

In obstetrics, the length of a pregnancy is often referred to as gestation in weeks+days.

â How long does a human pregnancy usually last? Do you know what this is as gestation (in weeks+days)?

ð¤°Preterm birth is when a baby is born before 37 weeks of pregnancy. It is estimated that over 13 million babies are born prematurely each year. Being born preterm increases risk of child illness and child death in children under 5 years old.

Why does preterm birth happen?

It is still unknown why preterm birth occurs and birth can be linked to multiple causes. Most preterm births happen spontaneously, and others can be due to medical conditions such as infections or complications during pregnancy.

There are many researchers working to understand how we may be able to identify someone at risk of preterm birth. This is very helpful as we can provide early treatment for women to reduce the likelihood of baby being born early.

The dataset we are using today are from researchers understanding the differences in the vaginal microbiota ð¦  by using techniques to sequence the bacterial DNA. They look at this data to see how there may be changes in the bacterial composition between women who have a preterm birth. In this session, we will become data detectives and see if we can identify any interesting insights from this dataset to help us better understand the relationship between the microbiota and preterm birthðµï¸.

Plotting the data

Another useful thing to do is to plot some of the values we have in the dataset. Visualising information as graphs ð can be very helpful!

One question we may want to ask is what the different modes of delivery by birth outcome are.

One option is to create a table with Outcome and DeliveryMode:

table(metadata$Outcome, metadata$DeliveryMode)
         
          CesareanDelivery NormalSpontaneousVaginalDelivery
  Preterm               23                               26
  Term                  13                               34
         
          OperativeVaginalDelivery
  Preterm                        0

We can see from the table there were more normal spontaneous vaginal deliveries in the term group compared to the preterm group (34 vs 26).

Instead of using tables, we could also show this information using a bar graph. Run the code below to generate a bar graph of the same data we have shown in the table above.

ggplot(metadata, aes(x = Outcome, fill = DeliveryMode)) + geom_bar(position = "dodge") + geom_text(aes(label = after_stat(count)), stat = 'count', position = position_dodge(0.9), vjust = -0.2) + labs(x = "Outcome", y = "Count", fill = "Delivery")

A boxplot is another useful plot we can use to visualise data. It helps us look at the spread and any potential skew. This is because it is divided into quartiles where:

  • Q0 = Minimum. Lowest data point (excluding any outliers)

  • Q1: Lower quartile (25th percentile). Median of the lower half of the dataset.

  • Q2 = Median. Middle value

  • Q3: Upper quartile (75th percentile). Median of the upper half of the dataset

  • Q4 = Maximum. Highest data point (excluding any outliers).

Body mass index (BMI) is used as a measure of body weight relative height, and is calculated using the formula: $\frac {weight (kg)}{height (m)^{2}}$

We could use a box plot to investigate whether there is a difference in BMI between women who deliver preterm vs term.

metadata %>%
  drop_na(BMI) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Outcome, y=BMI)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.colour="black", outlier.shape=8,
               outlier.size=2)

Looking at the box plot comparing BMI in women who delivered preterm vs term

âWhich of the two groups appears to have a higher median BMI

âIs there a way we can formally test if the difference is real

âCan you propose a suitable null hypothesis (where there is no difference between the two groups)

Statistical tests

In research, we often formulate a null hypothesis and use statistics to see whether we can reject the null hypothesis. In the example above, our null hypothesis is there is no difference BMI between the two groups (women who delivery preterm vs term).

We can use a t-test to understand if the difference in BMI is statistically significant. In R,we can use the t.test function.

t.test(BMI ~ Outcome, data = metadata, na.action = na.omit)

    Welch Two Sample t-test

data:  BMI by Outcome
t = 1.3042, df = 80.12, p-value = 0.1959
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Preterm and group Term is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 -1.650260  7.926168
sample estimates:
mean in group Preterm    mean in group Term 
             31.55133              28.41337

We can see the results of the t-test has a lot of different numbers included. Letâs try to break this down:

  • The mean BMI in the preterm group is 31.55

  • The mean BMI is the term group is 28.41

The p-value is >0.05, which means we do not reject the null hypothesis (and cannot claim a statistically significant difference in BMI between the two groups). The 95% confidence interval suggests that the true difference in the two groups is between -1.65 and 7.96.

Understanding the vaginal microbiota in preterm birth

In the study of microbiology and microbiomes, including the vaginal microbiome, researchers often analyse the composition of microbial communities by identifying and categorising the microorganisms present based on their taxonomic classification.

Taxonomic classification is a system to help understand the diversity and relationship between different microorganisms.

âCan you name some of the levels of the taxonomic hierarchy

âWhich is the broadest of these?

âWhich is the most specific?

Researchers have been studying the potential link between the vaginal microbiome and preterm birth, aiming to understand if microbial imbalances may contribute to an increased risk of preterm birth.

Next generation sequencing

Next-generation sequencing technologies have developed over the past 15-20 years and allows us to take DNA from a sample and sequence this.

The data that we are working with today has been sequenced from the vaginal microbiota using NGS. Letâs take a look at this data and integrate it with the metadata we were looking at earlier.

Operational Taxonomic Units (OTUs)

OTUs are groups of microorganisms that are similar to each other based on their genetic information. They are created by clustering sequences together that share a certain level of similarity. OTUs are used to represent different types of microorganisms in a microbial community.

Think of OTUs as groups of similar microorganisms, like a club where members have similar characteristics. Each OTU has a representative member that stands in for all the other members in that group. OTUs are helpful when itâs difficult to identify individual species in a diverse microbial community.

ð Over to you!

Taxonomy Tables

Taxonomy tables are like name tags that tell us the classification of each OTU. They show the taxonomic labels or names associated with each OTU, indicating their hierarchical position in the classification system (e.g., phylum, class, order, etc.).

Taxonomy tables help us understand what kinds of microorganisms are present in a microbial community. They provide information about the taxonomic composition and diversity, helping us identify the different groups of microorganisms that are part of the community.

Letâs have a look at the taxonomy table we will be using to assign our OTUs.

ð Over to you!

  2. Look at the first few rows of data
# taxonomy <- read.csv('taxonomy.csv', header = TRUE, row.names = 1)
# head(taxonomy)

The first column is the OTU sequence - similar to what we saw earlier in the otu.csv file. If you scroll to the right, you can see that each of these are assigned to their taxonomic ranks.

In summary, OTUs are groups of similar microorganisms, and taxonomy tables tell us the names and categories of those groups. Together, they help us understand the types and diversity of microorganisms in a microbial community.

Diving into the microbiota data

Using the OTU and taxonomy table you see above, we can start to get a glimpse of the all the DNA that has been sequenced using NGS technologies.

A note on using phyloseq to handle the microbiota data: Phyloseq is a package designed for the analysis and exploration of microbiota data. It helps us with importing, organizing, manipulating, and visualizing high-throughput sequencing data, particularly data obtained from 16S rRNA gene sequencing or metagenomic sequencing.

color_set <- c("coral1","orange", "darkgoldenrod", "chartreuse4", "springgreen3", "darkgreen", "darkslategray1", "deepskyblue", "deepskyblue4", "darkorchid1", "deeppink", "deeppink4")
